    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Gymnastics Bias</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hoi Wan John Louis letter questions why NBC cannot show entire block of one Olympic sport together and scores coverage of gymnastics</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>I found myself being annoyed with NBC's spreading out the swimming, gymnastics, baseball, etc., events to fill out an evening. Since these events already occurred, why can't NBC show the entire block of one sport together, followed by another entire block?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>I found myself being annoyed with NBC's spreading out the swimming, gymnastics, baseball, etc., events to fill out an evening. Since these events already occurred, why can't NBC show the entire block of one sport together, followed by another entire block?</p>
        <p>NBC has done a good job on the swimming; the reporting was even-handed. I wish the same could be said for early coverage of the gymnastics. The Ukrainian men won second place, yet only a handful of performances for that team was shown. Yes, the United States men's team had a chance to win the bronze, and I understand they should be shown. But if a performer blows a routine, couldn't Al Trautwig, Tim Daggett and Elfi Schlegel just say he/she missed the routine. The time saved could be used for the athletes who did hit their routines.</p>
        <p>HOI WAN JOHN LOUIS  New York City</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
